            "id": "a7cad08f6a5d40b883032",
            "questionText": "A high-speed train departs from a station, starting from rest. It accelerates uniformly to a speed of $!$30 \\ m/s$!$ in the first $!$15 \\ seconds$!$, maintains this uniform velocity for $!$45 \\ seconds$!$, and then decelerates uniformly from $!$30 \\ m/s$!$ to a complete stop over $!$10 \\ seconds$!$. Calculate the total distance travelled by the train during its entire journey, assuming its motion can be represented by a speed-time graph.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "49ce91f3122c4266b3fcf",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the concept that relates the area under a speed-time graph to the distance travelled. Please select the correct representation:",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "5fadf3e9-25eb-4d0c-b4c6-ba8237b81823"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\text{Distance = area under the speed-time graph}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\text{Distance = speed \\times time}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\text{Distance = acceleration \\times time}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\text{Distance = speed \\div time}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "faf7201337224341a094a",
                    "stepText": "Now, consider the acceleration phase where the train speeds up from 0 to $!$30 \\ m/s$!$ in $!$15 \\ s$!$. This portion of the graph forms a triangle. Which of the following is the correct formula for the area of a triangle?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\text{Area} = \\frac{1}{2} \\times \\text{base} \\times \\text{height}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\text{Area} = \\text{base} \\times \\text{height}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\text{Area} = \\frac{\\text{base} + \\text{height}}{2}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\text{Area} = \\text{base}^2 \\times \\text{height}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "68d584a719e64fb5aa206",
                    "stepText": "Using the triangle area formula, compute the distance covered during the acceleration phase. Here, the base is the time ($!$15 \\ s$!$) and the height is the final speed ($!$30 \\ m/s$!$). Calculate the area.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "225"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "6c0af32641dc485aaa486",
                    "stepText": "Next, consider the constant speed phase where the train travels at $!$30 \\ m/s$!$ for $!$45 \\ s$!$. Calculate the distance covered during this portion by multiplying the speed by the time.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
