        {
            "id": "ea352620b2874baf8c8c2",
            "questionText": "A cannon is positioned at the edge of a cliff, $!$100 \\text{ m}$!$ above sea level. It fires a cannonball horizontally with an initial speed of $!$50 \\text{ m/s}$!$. Neglecting air resistance, calculate the horizontal distance (range) from the base of the cliff where the cannonball lands. Assume the acceleration due to gravity is $!$g = 9.8 \\text{ m/s}^2$!$.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "7f37147c31b242c08530d",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the appropriate free-fall equation that relates the distance fallen and the time of fall for an object starting from rest. Please select the correct formula from the options below.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "bf356ebf-0c10-4ac7-83ad-d295081f17bf"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$s = \\frac{1}{2}gt^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$s = gt$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$t = \\frac{s}{g}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "09809412f8194139bab58",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now, using the free-fall formula you selected, compute the time taken by the cannonball to fall a vertical distance of $!$100 \\text{ m}$!$. (Hint: Rearrange the equation to solve for $!$t$!$ and substitute $!$s = 100 \\text{ m}$!$ and $!$g = 9.8 \\text{ m/s}^2$!$.)",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "4.52"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "s",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "bf356ebf-0c10-4ac7-83ad-d295081f17bf",
                        "4dfaa3d5-ea53-4fcf-abef-a1c95e17effc"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "287d3a44650b474383bc2",
                    "stepText": "Now, let's identify the correct formula for calculating the horizontal distance traveled by an object moving at constant speed. Choose the formula that correctly relates horizontal distance, speed, and time.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
